The approach taken in the provided solution is to simplify the expression by cancelling out common factors in the numerator and denominator before multiplying. This is an efficient method as it reduces the number of calculations required and makes the problem easier to solve. By recognizing that $9!$ appears in both the numerator and denominator, we can cancel it out, leaving only the factors from 10 to 14 in the numerator and the factors from 2 to 5 in the denominator.
Step 1: Expand the numerator and denominator using the definition of factorial:
$$\begin{align*}
\frac{14!}{5!9!} &= \frac{14 \cdot 13 \cdot 12 \cdot 11 \cdot 10 \cdot 9!}{5 \cdot 4 \cdot 3 \cdot 2 \cdot 9!}
\end{align*}$$

Step 2: Cancel out the common factor of $9!$ in the numerator and denominator:
$$\begin{align*}
\frac{14 \cdot 13 \cdot 12 \cdot 11 \cdot 10 \cdot 9!}{5 \cdot 4 \cdot 3 \cdot 2 \cdot 9!} &= \frac{14 \cdot 13 \cdot 12 \cdot 11 \cdot 10}{5 \cdot 4 \cdot 3 \cdot 2}
\end{align*}$$

Step 3: Simplify the remaining factors in the numerator and denominator:
$$\begin{align*}
\frac{14 \cdot 13 \cdot 12 \cdot 11 \cdot 10}{5 \cdot 4 \cdot 3 \cdot 2} &= \frac{14 \cdot 13 \cdot 12 \cdot 11}{4 \cdot 3}
\end{align*}$$

Step 4: Multiply the remaining factors in the numerator and denominator:
$$\begin{align*}
\frac{14 \cdot 13 \cdot 12 \cdot 11}{4 \cdot 3} &= 14 \cdot 13 \cdot 11 \\
&= 2002
\end{align*}$$

The key insight in this solution is to simplify the product by canceling out common factors between numerators and denominators. By writing out the first few terms and the last few terms of the product, we can see that most of the terms cancel out, leaving only the numerators of the last three terms and the denominators of the first three terms.
1. Write out the product explicitly:
$$\begin{align*}
\prod_{n = 1}^{20} \frac{n + 3}{n} &= \frac{4}{1} \cdot \frac{5}{2} \cdot \frac{6}{3} \cdot \frac{7}{4} \dotsm \frac{20}{17} \cdot \frac{21}{18} \cdot \frac{22}{19} \cdot \frac{23}{20}
\end{align*}$$

2. Notice that the denominators of the first 17 terms are equal to the numerators of the first 17 terms minus 3. This means that these terms will cancel out when multiplied together, leaving only the numerators of the last three terms and the denominators of the first three terms:
$$\begin{align*}
\prod_{n = 1}^{20} \frac{n + 3}{n} &= \frac{21 \cdot 22 \cdot 23}{1 \cdot 2 \cdot 3}
\end{align*}$$

3. Calculate the remaining product:
$$\begin{align*}
\frac{21 \cdot 22 \cdot 23}{1 \cdot 2 \cdot 3} &= \frac{10626}{6} = 1771
\end{align*}$$

The key insight in this problem is recognizing the inverse proportionality between the number of men and the number of days required to complete the job. By setting up an equation using this relationship and a constant $k$, we can easily solve for the unknown variable when given the other values. This approach allows us to efficiently calculate the number of days needed for a different number of men working at the same rate.
The number of men and the amount of time to dig the foundation are inversely proportional.  Let $m$ equal the number of men and $d$ equal the number of days to complete the foundation.  This implies that $md=k$ for some constant $k$.  From the given information, $15\cdot 4=60=k$.  Knowing the value of $k$ we can solve for the number of days it would have have taken 25 men to dig the foundation: $$\begin{align*}
25\cdot d&=60\\
\Rightarrow\qquad d&=60/25=12/5=\boxed{2.4}
\end{align*}$$
It would have taken 25 men approximately 2.4 days to dig the foundation.
